My impression of visiting Cambridge is that it's like the Disneyland version of Oxford. Now, I love Disneyland and Cambridge is very pretty indeed, prettier than Oxford on the surface, but I don't mean this as a compliment in this context. There is a hollowness to Cambridge. It is like a Pepper's Ghost trick of something probably going on at Oxford. It is flat and the people and weather can be kind of icy. It is not somewhere that I would feel 'looked after'. Cambridge, being situated in more of a cultural vacuum than Oxford in terms of the counties that surround it, has, in a way, regrettably easily absorbed much of that anonymous 'I don't care about you' London energy. It is a bit bizarre that an equal of Oxford ever found sufficient footing there. I look at the front of King's College Cambridge and it's just an ornate facade. I might as well be looking at Brighton Pavillion.

Been there on a 7-weeks-trip around BB, Moorea, Tahiti, Cook Islands/Rarotonga, Fiji and Tonga / Fafa Island. I was disappointed by Fiji, impressed by Rarotonga and OVERWHELMED by the beautiful colors of Bora Bora. And when I looked down on the side of my bed made of Bamboo, I looked through a "window" in the floor going from the inside of my Overwater-Bungalow (Sofitel-Marara) into the water of the Lagoon. It was worth every penny! Of course the California Coast, Lake Tahoe, New Zealand and the beautiful Islands of the Philippines are beautiful - but Bora Bora just beats everything I've seen. Go there - and you will never regret it. Good Luck, Martin.

My wife and I stayed at the Sofitel on Bora Bora for a week in 1983 then a week on Moorea. We had a wonderful two weeks in Polynesia. I am sad to see Bora Bora so over developed now. The private motu that the hotel owns had not been developed at that time. They would boat you over for the day or a few hours if you wanted to go. You had the entire motu to yourself. 
We knew that was a once in a lifetime vacation for us. It is still gorgeous and if you can go, you will not regret it.
